<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>HM Treasury Consultation</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by CCSA (HOT36)</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Carbon Capture and Storage Association </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">welcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> opportunity to respond to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Energy and Climate Change Committee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Inquiry into Heat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We recognise the importance of heat as an energy consumer in the UK and the need to decarbonise heat in a sustainable and cost-effective manner.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The CCSA brings together a wide range of specialist com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">panies across the spectrum of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Carbon Capture &amp; Storage (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> technology, as well as a variety of support services to the energy sector. The Association exists to represent the interests of its members in promoting the business of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and to assist policy d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evelopments in the UK and the EU towards a long term regulatory framework for CCS, as a means of abating carbon dioxide emissions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">General comments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The need to provide sufficient heat to meet demand, whilst still meeting climate change objectives is beco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ming increasingly important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. DECC published </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Future of Heating: Meeting the challenge in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in March 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (the ‘Heat Strategy’)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in which they set out the options </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the supply of low carbon heat in the UK. Whilst the CCSA recognises the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">challenge of supplying low-carbon heat, the important role that carbon capture and storage (CCS) can play in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enabling the Heat Strategy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has not been sufficiently recognised. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Heat Strategy was informed by modelling carried out by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Redpoint</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – which was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">based on a study looking at “Pathways for Decarbonising Heat”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This study looked at the complete energy system (power, heat and transport) and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">modelled a number of different pathways to achieve the UK’s statutory target of reducing greenhouse gas emission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s by 80% by 2050. The least-cost scenarios make extensive use of CCS by 2050</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and emphasise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the vital role that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CCS can play in enabling a range of affordable options to decarbonise heat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in particular:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The combination of CCS with power stations and Combi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ned Heat and Power (CHP) to provide low-carbon heat through heat networks</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Capturing emissions in industry through CCS, and using CCS on fossil fuels to provide low-carbon electricity and heating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for industry</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Using CCS to produce low-carbon hydrogen – which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can be used to power heat networks, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">combining CCS with biomass to deliver negative emissions</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The study showed that pathways without CCS would require exceptional levels of power from nuclear and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">renewables</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – to support increased electrification of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e heating and transport sectors. The development of low-carbon heat networks with CHP would soon become limited due to emissions constraints and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the absence of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CCS would have a significant impact on the potential for wide-scale roll-out of hydrogen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as a fu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">el source for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> low-carbon heat.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">CHP w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ith CCS – Providing Low Carbon P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ower and District Heat </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One of the key technologies for supplying low-cost energy efficient heating is through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CHP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, however CHP still emits carbon dioxide (albeit at a lower level than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an unabated power station. On the other hand, power plants with CCS incur an energy penalty, but emit almost zero carbon dioxide. Therefore, the combination of CHP and CCS pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vides </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comple</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mentarity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the supply of low-carbon heat.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To supply low-carbon hea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t through the combination of CCS and CHP will require integration of CCS into the design of the CHP plant from the start. This is because both CCS and CHP have fundamental design requirements for the host plant to optimise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">energy consumption and therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CCS cannot be considered as an ‘add-on’ to CHP. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK National Policy Statements (planning policy for Nationally Signi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ficant Infrastructure Projects), which came into force in July 2011, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include a requirement for all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">combustion power stations (at or over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">300MW) to be constructed Carbon Capture Ready</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (CCR)</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This requirement also extends to any CHP plant at or above 300 MW. There is therefore a need to ensure that any developer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">designing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a CHP plant, appropriately considers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the CCS design requirements that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would enable the plant to be considered CCR, and there is also a need to ensure incentives are in place that will enable the CHP plant to retrofit CCS when necessary.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Although the current CCR requirement only applies to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">combustion power stations over 300MW</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, we would strongly recommend that CHP plants below 300MW should also be encouraged to consider CCS design requirements – as smaller CHP plants will also need to decarbonise to supply low-carbon heat.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In addition, the Industrial Emissions Directive will ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">use developers to consider modifications that may be necessary to ensure compliance. Such modifications may include installation of CHP to replace </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">industrial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">boilers – and it is again important to ensure that any such modifications are built with CCS in mi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd, to enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> emissions reductions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The supply of heating in the UK is particularly important for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">domestic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and commercial buildings, which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consume by far the largest amount of energy for he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ating in the UK. The majority of heating in buildings is met using gas-fired boilers (for space and hot water), and there are a number of options for decarbonising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heat including CHP and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a switch from gas-fired boilers to low-carbon electricity for he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ating. The Heat Strategy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">identifies the concern that peak demand for heating occurs in the coldest days in winter – and this places a great strain on our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heat </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supply networks. However, there is an additional concern where low temperatures combine with low </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wind speeds during seasonal anticyclone patter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s – as the supply of heating in these periods will rely on low-carbon electricity to meet demand, and this highlights the importance of fossil fuels with CCS.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> To decarbonise heat in buildings through electrici</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ty will require a large switch of heat load from unabated domestic gas burn </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to electric heat. This electric heat will result in a huge increase in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">future generation load – which needs to be decarbonised and available during cold, windless periods. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Compared</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to other forms of intermittent and inflexible low-carbon electricity, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CCS on fossil fuels </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">represents a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reliable, readily-available </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">source of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">low-carbon electricity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore has a vital role to play in providing decarbonised electricity for heat g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oing forward.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Decarbonising Heat in Industry</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Heat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">integral to many processes in some of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">key industrial sectors in the UK, such as steel, cement, refining and chemicals. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With 20% of the UK’s total energy consumed in industry as heat, and industry generating one third of the UK’s heat-related carbon emissions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– there is a clear need to decarbonise industrial heat. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Due to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">requirement for high-grade </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heat </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in many of the in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dustrial sectors, fossil fuels currently supply the larg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e majority of heat in industry. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Heat Strategy rightly places a large emphasis on the need to decarbonise heat in industry, however we are concerned with the lack of integration with the overall </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approach to decarbonise industry in general. The Heat Strategy considers decarbonising heat as separate to other activities and technologies that may be pursued by different sectors for carbon abatement and it is essential that decarbonising industrial hea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is pursued as part of a wider strategy to achieve overall decarbonisation of industry. Such an overall strategy must recognise the vital role that CCS will play in decarbonising industry – indeed for a number of industrial sectors, CCS is the only option</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for significant carbon abatement due to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the fact that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">carbon dioxide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> unavoidably produced as part of the chemical and manufacturing process.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A number of studies point to the importance of CCS for carbon abatement in industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the IEA CCS Roadmap 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to limit global temperature increases to 2°C by 2050, CCS will need to contribute around 14% of emissions reductions, and almost half (45%) of the carbon dioxide captured will need to come from industrial applications</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK cement industry re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">published a strategy for reducing greenhouse gas emissions in the sector – CCS is instrumental to reach the more ambitious target of an 81% reduction in emissions by 2050</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The TUC together with the Energy Intensive Users Group (EIUG) last year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">published a report setting out the need for a coherent UK industrial strategy to secure energy-intensive industries in a UK low-carbon economy – the report emphasises the importance of CCS as a key technology that could make a difference to industry now</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many industrial sectors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have already undertaken actions to reduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emissions and improve efficiency, and most ‘low hanging fruit’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have already been pursued with limited further improvements that can be achieved. For a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">number of sectors, breakthrough/step</span><span style="font-family:'Cambria Math'; font-size:12pt">‐</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hange technologi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es such as CCS offer tremendous </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">solutions to decarbonise. Some sectors could pursue CCS as soon as cost</span><span style="font-family:'Cambria Math'; font-size:12pt">‐</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effective transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and storage options become available, whilst others may require a process of pilots and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demonstrations ahead of comm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ercial deployment of these technologies by the 2030s.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The cost of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> capture from industrial activities actually represents some of the most cost-effective carbon abatement options in the UK. This is because many of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">these industries already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">produce almos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t pure streams of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as part of the process – resulting in a cost of capture significantly lower than the cost of capture in the power sector (and significantly cheaper than some carbon abatement policies currently being pursued in the UK)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It is notable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that all the current CCS projects operating in the world today (according to the Global CCS Institute) are capturing CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from industrial activities</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">CCS – The Potential</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crucial to the successful deployment of CCS (and therefore the deployment of CCS in industry) is the development of transport and storage infrastructure that can service future power and industrial emitters. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Developing right</span><span style="font-family:'Cambria Math'; font-size:12pt">‐</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sized infrastructure alongside </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the first CCS power projects will enable the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development of low</span><span style="font-family:'Cambria Math'; font-size:12pt">‐</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cost, early opportunity Industrial CCS proj</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ects as well as pilot scale and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demonstration projects.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Indeed, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ndustry has limited funds available to invest in infrastructure and a very limited o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pportunity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to pass additional infrastructure costs through to consumers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – and therefore the existence and availability of right-sized infrastructure will be vital to ensure the retention of many important industries in the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK has the geographic ad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vantage of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a large number of emitters </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(power and Industrial) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">located in clusters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> around major estuaries – with easy access to significant CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> storage potential in the North Sea. This lends itself extremely well to the development of CCS in a cluste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r approach – using common transport and storage infrastructure that can take CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from both power and industrial facilities, and transport this for permanent storage. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The development of heat networks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (for example using CHP) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is seen as an important approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in supplying decarbonised heat for industry and such heat networks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will require infrastructure development in the same way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as CCS, particularly as these will most likely use similar cluster</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s of industry as CCS to exploit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">economies of scale.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Consideration should therefore be given to the co-location of heat networks and CCS clusters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, to ensure a coordinated approach to the cost-effective decarbonisation of heat in industry. One particular benefit of such a coordinated approach would be the av</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ailability of CHP to generate steam for CCS capture processes – a possibility already being considered by a number of sectors investigating CCS.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Looking into the future, where even a small number of CHP plant are located close together at an industrial sit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e, it may be interesting to explore the possibility of collecting the flue gases from each site and transporting these to a central capture facility – thereby further harnessing economies of scale and allowing cost-effective decarbonisation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An effective way to decarbonise heating systems is to use hydrogen as a fuel. There are two ways to generate hydrogen. One way is electrolysis of water and there has been much discussion about the use of renewable power to fuel this process. This is a very</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> expensive solution particularly if used in combination with intermittent sources such as wind or solar. Electricity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">produced from renewable sources </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is already a high quality, clean energy source and should be used as such without </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">converting into hydrogen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">resulting in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further efficiency loss. The second way is to make hydrogen by chemical reforming of natural gas or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">syngas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> produces from coal. This process is highly cost-effective, is extensively used in the chemical industry and oil refining and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lends itsel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f to efficient carbon capture. It is very easy to envisage the use of hydrogen fuel for industrial and commercial heating. For domestic and commercial heating, at least as an interim measure a proportion (perhaps 15%) of hydrogen can be introduced into gas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> supplies. This would be a very significant saving overall. There already exists widespread hydrogen infrastructure networks in the industrial heartlands, for example in Teesside, Merseyside and around the low countries of Europe. In developing policies fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r decarbonising heat, it will therefore be important to consider the co-location of heat networks, CCS clusters and hydrogen infrastructure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It must be noted that heat networks can be powered by a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">number of different power plant options</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">renew</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and nuclear, as well as coal, gas and biomass plant with CCS (the latter is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particularly important as biomass with CCS would result in negative emissions). There is also the potential to produce hydrogen from CCS (as mentioned above) and where CCS cl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">usters </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are co-located with heat networks, there is the potential to use decarbonised hydrogen as a power source for the heat network. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where thermal generation and fossil fuels persist into the future (to power heat networks), there will be a need for CCS t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o ensure these important sources of energy are decarbonised. It is therefore important to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">synergies between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policies for decarbonising heat </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policies for electricity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are fully explored and captured</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">The view expressed in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">this paper cannot be taken to represent the views of all members of the CCSA. However, they do reflect a general consensus within the Association.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Redpoint</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> (report for National Grid), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Pathways for decarbonising heat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">, October 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Overarching National Policy Statement for Energy (EN-1), July 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> IEA </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Technology Roadmap CCS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">, July 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> MPA Cement 2050 Strategy, March 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> TUC/EIUG </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Building our low-carbon industries</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">, July 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> GCCSI </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Global Status of CCS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> 2012</span></p></body></html>